    "narrative": "For April 7, the analytical model highlights **Mickey Moniak** (75.75) and **Vinnie Pasquantino** (74.83) as our premier starts. **Mickey Moniak** benefits from a massive 14% park factor boost and a highly favorable platoon matchup against Burrows, while **Vinnie Pasquantino** takes advantage of a leaky 4.35 xERA arm in Williams. We are also prioritizing stolen base potential today; **Corbin Carroll** (68.01) is a mandatory start despite facing a tough arm in Peralta. The model specifically tagged the slow delivery of Peralta, which grants **Corbin Carroll** a 4% boost to his already elite sprint speed efficiency, making him a primary engine for our category scarcity needs.\n\nThe lineup construction remains disciplined, with **Jazz Chisholm Jr.** (73.11) and **James Wood** (73.10) serving as our strongest anchors against Civale and Liberatore. While **Jose Caballero** remains in the lineup due to his positional necessity, his score of 50.78 is suppressed by his #9 slot in the order and a negative platoon split. On the bubble, **Zach McKinstry** was the closest to cracking the starting nine (50.73). He was ultimately benched because his efficiency profile against Bradley, T is inferior to our current utility and middle infield options; we are preserving his game cap for a matchup with a higher ceiling. \n\nWe must monitor **Gabriel Moreno** and **Josh Naylor** closely, as both are operating right at the threshold of our \"marginal\" scoring tier (sub-51). Facing Peralta and Eovaldi\u2014both sub-3.70 xERA arms\u2014these two represent our highest risk of dragging down our daily efficiency. While **Austin Riley** (60.58) provides a solid floor, his matchup against Kikuchi necessitates a careful eye on early-game plate appearances to ensure we aren't chasing empty outs. No severe weather flags are present, but the combination of high-tier opposing starters makes this a day to prioritize our high-speed, high-OBP assets over raw power.",
